## Warning: package 'ggthemes' was built under R version 4.1.1
# Cleaned our data

survey = read.csv("DATA1001-survey-altered.csv")

library(tidyverse)

survey_fresh = survey %>%
                    rename(
                      `Age` = 2,
                      `LGA` = 3,
                      `Opinion on lockdown` = 4,
                      `Following rules` = 5,
                      `Cohabitation` = 6,
                      `Income` = 7,
                      `Lockdown time outdoors` = 8, 
                      `Lockdown time exercising` = 9,
                      `Exercise hours` = 10,
                      `Low mood` = 11,
                      `Happy mood` = 12,
                      `Hours technology` = 13
                       )
# str(survey_fresh)
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(survey_fresh, aes(x = survey_fresh$"Happy mood", y = survey_fresh$"Hours technology")) +
  geom_point()

## instead.
## Warning: Use of `survey_fresh$"Hours technology"` is discouraged. Use `Hours
## technology` instead.

## [1] -0.6290772
R1 = lm(survey_fresh$`Exercise hours` ~ survey_fresh$`Low mood`)

ggplot(survey_fresh, aes(y=R1$residuals, x=survey_fresh$`Low mood`)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept=0, colour = "aquamarine3", size = 1) +
  theme_classic() +
  labs (
    title = "Residuals",
    x = "Exercise hours",
    y = "Low mood"
  )

1 Premises

1.1 Strongly correlated - As weekly exercise declines, days of low mood increases - Vice versa for happy mood

1.2 Those in LGAs of concern will show the greatest exercise decline of all locales

2 Hence, those in LGAs of concern are the least happy during lockdown

3 As opinion on lockdown increases, as does rule-following
